{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512470"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:55:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:55:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11898"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583601"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:21:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:21:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11898"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11898"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.05,0.81,0.09,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4495"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45937"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4495"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11898"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30884"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"40"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1957"},{"type":"tags","id":"2254"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10538"},{"type":"tags","id":"10550"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6604"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6619"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9822"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11630"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45937","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/45937"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old man is brought to the emergency department with an altered sensorium. He is confused, lethargic and not able to provide any additional information.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis blood pressure is 85/60 mmHg, pulse 115/min and temperature 37.9\u02daC. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis initial laboratory studies show: sodium 133 mmol/L (135-145), potassium 2.4 mmol/L (3.5-5.0), chloride 97 mmol/L (98-105), HCO3 50 mmol/L (22-28), urea 44 mmol/L (8-20), creatinine 150 umol/L (60-115), albumin 35 g/L (35-50). An arterial blood gas shows PO2 of 69 mmHg (75-100), PCO2 of 47 mmHg (35-45), and pH of 7.55 (7.35-7.45).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following acid-base disorders is present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Metabolic acidosis with raised anion gap","Respiratory acidosis with adequate metabolic compensation","Metabolic alkalosis with inadequate respiratory compensation","Respiratory alkalosis with inadequate metabolic compensation","Respiratory alkalosis with adequate metabolic compensation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has \u003Cstrong\u003Emetabolic alkalosis (response C) \u003C/strong\u003Ebecause the pH is high (7.55) in the context of an elevated bicarbonate level (50)\u003Cstrong\u003E.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlkalaemia is defined as an elevation of the body\u0027s blood pH above 7.45.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMetabolic alkalosis is a primary increase in bicarbonate (HCO\u003Csub\u003E3\u003C/sub\u003E\u003Csup\u003E\u2212\u003C/sup\u003E) with or without a compensatory increase in carbon dioxide partial pressure (Pco\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommon causes include prolonged vomiting, hypovolaemia, diuretic use and hypokalaemia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn a metabolic alkalosis, the compensatory response is hypoventilation in an attempt to retain CO2 (and therefore decrease blood pH). To calculate whether a compensatory response is adequate, we can use the \u0027Bedside Rules\u0027. For a metabolic alkalosis, this rule is \u0027Rule 6\u0027, the \u0027Point 7 Plus 20 Rule\u0027:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExpected pCO2 = 0.7 [HCO3-] + 20 mmHg, +/- 5 mmHg\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore, the expected pCO2 in this patient would be:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpCO2 = 0.7(50) + 20 = 55 (+/- 5)mmHg\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe small disparity in HCO3- levels (in this case, 47mmHg compared with the expected 50mmHg) is common and is most in keeping with inadequate respiratory compensation rather than a primary respiratory acidosis\u003Cstrong\u003E (response B)\u003C/strong\u003E. NB: expected CO2 should never result in an apparent \u0022over-compensation\u0022 disparity, ie. the CO2 level will never be higher \u0022just in case\u0022. If the CO2 were observed to be greater than the expected compensatory mechanism, this would indicate a separate respiratory acidosis process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA concomitant partial \u003Cstrong\u003Erespiratory alkalosis (response D and E) \u003C/strong\u003Ecausing a CO2 lower than expected is a much less likely explanation. Some causes of secondary respiratory alkalosis in the context of alkalaemia could be hyperventilation due to either pain or fluid overload. However, of note this would be a secondary or separate process that would result in a \u003Cem\u003Elower\u003C/em\u003E bicarbonate level, which is not observed in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis is not a \u003Cstrong\u003Emetabolic acidosis (response A)\u003C/strong\u003E, as the bicarbonate level is elevated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Alkalaemia is an elevation of the body\u0027s pH above 7.45.","Metabolic alkalosis involves a primary increase in serum bicarbonate (HCO3-) concentration, due to a loss of H+ from the body or a gain in HCO3-.","The \u0027Bedside Rules\u0027 can help determine the primary acid-base disturbance and the  adequacy of compensatory responses"],"references":["Hamilton PK, Morgan NA, Connolly GM, Maxwell AP. Understanding Acid-Base Disorders. Ulster Med J. 2017 Sep;86(3):161-166. Epub 2017 Sep 12.","Brandis K. Acid Base Physiology -Contents [Internet]. www.anaesthesiamcq.com. 2015. Available from: https://www.anaesthesiamcq.com/AcidBaseBook/ABindex.php"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30884"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11898"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30884","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/30884"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-24T13:56:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-05-24T13:56:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4495"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45937"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":nul